\begin{frame}
\frametitle{\CHAPTER. Developing a population version of the linear model}

\vspace{-1mm}

\begin{myitemize}
\item We now know how to set up a linear model explaining a response variable \m{\vec{y}} using a matrix of explanatory variables \m{\mat{X}}. 
We write \m{\vec{y}=\mat{X}\vec{b}+\vec{e}} and use least squares to estimate the coefficient vector, \m{\vec{b}}.
We understand that this is a compact way of writing \m{y_i = x_{i1}b_1 + x_{i2}b_2 + \dots + x_{ip}b_p + e_i} for \m{i=1,\dots,n}.

\item Generically, we call \m{y_i} the response for \myemph{individual} $i$. 
We think of an individual as a row in the dataset.
In some situations, this terminology is counter-intuitive, for example in HW3 when we consider a dataset where there are four rows of data for each kicker.

\item A positive value of \m{b_j} for \m{j} in \m{\{1,\dots,p\}} means that larger values of the \m{j}th predictor variable are associated with larger values of the response. 

\item Suppose the individuals are randomly drawn from some sample. Common statistical questions are:

(a) How much would our estimate of \m{b_j} change if we had a different sample?

(b) Is there convincing evidence that \m{b_j\neq 0}? If not, we could remove the \m{j}th predictor from the model.

\end{myitemize}

\end{frame}


\begin{frame}[fragile]
\frametitle{Population inference needs a probability model}

\begin{myitemize}
\item A probability model for a data vector \m{\vec{y}} uses \myemph{random variables} to model how the data were generated.

\item Probability models let us assign probabilities to events that may or may not occur, such as ``What is the probability that the difference between the estimated coefficient \m{b_1} and the true coefficient is smaller than \m{0.1}.'' 

\item We have the following goals:

\begin{itemize}
\item \quad Review the rules of probability.
\item \quad Build the skills needed to work with probabilities for linear models.
\item \quad Learn to check our probability calculations using R.
\item \quad Use probability calculations to develop statistical inference procedures for linear models.
\end{itemize}
\end{myitemize}

\end{frame}


\begin{frame}[fragile]
\frametitle{Review of probability}

\begin{myitemize}
\item The \myemph{probability} of an event is the long-run proportion of times that an event would happen in a large number of datasets drawn from the probability model.

