\begin{frame}[fragile]
\frametitle{Potential outcomes, events, and their probability}

\vspace{-2mm}

\begin{myitemize}
\item A \myemph{potential outcome} of a probability model is any dataset that could be generated by the model.
   
% \hspace{3mm} Example 1. The set of potential outcomes when tossing a fair coin can be modeled as \m{\{H,T\}}.

% \hspace{3mm} 
\item {\bf Example}. The set of potential outcomes when rolling a 6-sided die can be modeled as \m{\{1,2,3,4,5,6\}}.

% \hspace{3mm} A subtle modeling assumption: we ignore the possibility that the coin can land on its edge, or the die can roll off the table.

\item An \myemph{event} is a collection of potential outcomes.

\item An event \m{A} can either happen or not happen on any \myemph{realization} of the model.

\item \m{\prob(A)} is the \myemph{probability} that \m{A} happens according to the model.

\item If each outcome is equally likely (e.g., a roll of a fair die) we can generate realizations of the random variable in R using \code{sample()}

% \hspace{3mm} 
